s=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dorothy_Crowfoot_Hodgkin#cite_note-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dorothy_Crowfoot_Hodgkin#cite_note-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-bio_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dorothy_Crowfoot_Hodgkin#cite_note-bio-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>She advanced the technique of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/X-ray_crystallography\" title=\"X-ray crystallography\">X-ray crystallography<\/a>, a method used to determine the three-dimensional structures of biomolecules. Among her most influential discoveries are the confirmation of the structure of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Penicillin\" title=\"Penicillin\">penicillin<\/a> that <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernst_Boris_Chain\" title=\"Ernst Boris Chain\">Ernst Boris Chain<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edward_Abraham\" title=\"Edward Abraham\">Edward Abraham<\/a> had previously surmised, and then the structure of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vitamin_B12\" title=\"Vitamin B12\">vitamin B<sub>12<\/sub><\/a>, for which she became the third woman to win the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Prize\">Nobel Prize<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chemistry\" title=\"Chemistry\">Chemistry<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-bio_8-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dorothy_Crowfoot_Hodgkin#cite_note-bio-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>In 1969, after 35 years of work and five years after winning the Nobel Prize, Hodgkin was able to decipher the structure of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Insulin\" title=\"Insulin\">insulin<\/a>. X-ray crystallography became a widely used tool and was critical in later determining the structures of many biological molecules where knowledge of structure is critical to an understanding of function. She is regarded as one of the pioneer scientists in the field of X-ray crystallography studies of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biomolecule\" title=\"Biomolecule\">biomolecules<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Dorothy Crowfoot Hodgkin","place_of_birth":"Cairo, Egypt","place_of_death":"Ilmington ,  Warwickshire , England","text":"Dorothy Crowfoot Hodgkin , Chemistry, 1964","year":1964.0}